ce><gtr:abstractText>Neutrino oscillation experiments have produced the 'smoking gun' for non-zero neutrino mass studying atmospheric and solar neutrinos. This is one of the most exciting discoveries in particle physics in several decades as it gives us the first definitive evidence for physics beyond the Standard Model. It is now time for a new type of experiments which will use controllable neutrino beams to measure the actual values of the neutrino mixing parameters. The first experiment to do it with high precision will be the MINOS long-baseline neutrino oscillation project. By 2008 it will provide a measurement of the oscillation parameters with a 10% accuracy which is one of the goals of this scientific proposal. There are two remaining questions that cannot be answered by oscillation experiments. Because neutrinos carry no electric charge, there is a possibility, much favoured by theoretical models, that the neutrinos are of Majorana type where the neutrino is its own antiparticle. Neutrinoless double beta decay experiments are the only way to resolve this issue. The other question is about the absolute neutrino mass scale. The best current limit for the absolute electron neutrino mass of Mayorana type comes from double beta decay experiments. One of the goals of this proposal is to improve this sensitivity to ~0.1 eV with an existing experiment (NEM03) and to develop a realistic project to reach ~0.03 eV in the next 5-10 years. Leadership in neutrino oscillation and decay experiments will put the UK in the enviable position of having been pivotal in solving the neutrino mass puzzle.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/D7F4F462-0518-4784-908A-D12633C139B3"><gtr:id>D7F4F462-0518-4784-908A-D12633C139B3</gtr:id><gtr:name>STFC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2004-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>236269</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artist